The paper deals with developing an algorithm for player modelling and inference in trick-taking card games, which involves probabilistic reasoning and decision-making. This aligns with the sub-categories of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), Game Theory (cs.GT), and Learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of policies and strategies in the algorithm, which falls under the sub-category of Programming Languages (cs.PL). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of large information sets, which is a common issue in Search and Optimization (cs.SI).
